TAMIL NADU BLOCKCHAIN POLICY 2020

1. Introduction
Tamil Nadu aims to use blockchain for transparent, secure, and efficient e-governance.
Inspired by Estonia, Singapore, Georgia; India and TN are exploring blockchain for land, healthcare, and digital identity.
TN State-wide Blockchain Backbone announced by Hon’ble CM for secure government services.

2. Why Blockchain in e-Governance?
Enables inter-departmental data sharing and accountability.
Secures citizen documents via tamper-proof digital copies.
Supports supply chains, health records, identity management, and citizen benefits.
Smart contracts enable automated and auditable workflows.

3. Goals & Objectives
Goals:
Make TN a global blockchain leader.
Deliver secure, fast, and transparent services.
Promote awareness and adoption among officials.
Build a thriving ecosystem of startups, researchers, and professionals.
Primary Objectives:
Standardize design, security, and deployment of blockchain apps.
Build a self-sustaining blockchain community.
Create regulatory sandbox for experimentation.
Form oversight mechanisms for adoption and rollout.



4. Applicability
Government bodies, PSUs, cooperatives, trusts, boards, and joint ventures under TN government.

5. Implementation Strategy
Build state-wide blockchain backbone for G2G and G2C services.
Prioritize high-impact use cases.
Establish standards & guidelines for blockchain apps.
Conduct capacity building for government officials.
Encourage adoption via Blockchain Forum – Nambikkai Inaiyam Manram.
Provide regulatory sandbox for testing blockchain applications.
Oversight through dedicated committees.

6. TN State-Wide Blockchain Backbone
Hybrid blockchain platform (cloud/on-premise) for multiple stakeholders.
Modular architecture reduces development time & cost.
TNeGA manages seed nodes, with departments adding nodes for apps.
Supports Blockchain-as-a-Service (BaaS) for external stakeholders.
Ensures data accuracy, deduplication, and interoperability.

7. Key Use Cases
Data integrity and audit trails for government documents.
Secure academic records and certificates.
Portable digital identity and privacy-preserving workflows.
Cybersecurity for government portals.
Land registration and inter-departmental workflows.
Agricultural produce tracking.
Secure healthcare data storage and transmission.
Blockchain-enabled benefit distribution.


8. Guidelines for Blockchain Applications
Committees (Implementation, Protocols & Standards, Legal) audit platforms and enforce standards.
Standards cover:
Consensus mechanisms, governance framework, enterprise development
Privacy, consent, identity & key management
Smart contract design, deployment, versioning
Data preprocessing, archiving, bug reporting, SOPs for network lifecycle
Applications must follow mobile-first approach, privacy-preserving workflows, and be interoperable with backbone.

9. Capacity Building
Workshops, hackathons, bootcamps for cross-department learning.
Professional courses for executives and officers to understand blockchain risks and opportunities.

10. Encouragement for Adoption
Blockchain Ecosystem Forum – connect startups, academia, and industry.
App Development Platform – modular, API-driven development environment.
Regulatory Sandbox – semi-regulated environment for testing apps before production.

11. Oversight Mechanism – Committees
Committee
Role
TN Blockchain Policy Implementation Committee
Drive policy adoption, guide blockchain backbone roadmap, monitor milestones
Protocols & Standards Committee
Enforce security, coding, smart contract standards, governance framework
Legal & Regulatory Committee
Ensure compliance with laws, privacy standards, smart contract arbitration, ethical usage


12. Key Features of Blockchain Adoption
Immutable, decentralized, and auditable data storage.
High security and reduced dependency on intermediaries.
Transparency and accountability in workflows.

13. Challenges
Shortage of skilled blockchain professionals.
High setup costs.
Integration with legacy systems.
Need for continuous legal and technical updates.

14. Future Scope
Expansion into smart cities and AI/IoT integration.
Use in public finance monitoring.
Making TN a technology-driven governance hub.

15. Recent News & Facts
TN e-Governance Agency leads the state-wide blockchain backbone.
Encourages startups and MSMEs to develop blockchain applications.
Policy referenced in Times of India (2019): TN govt services to become hassle-free using high-tech blockchain solutions.

Exam-Ready One-Line Summary
Tamil Nadu Blockchain Policy 2020 aims to leverage blockchain for secure, transparent, and efficient governance while promoting innovation and ecosystem development.



